        <h1>1. <%= @page_title_1 %></h1>
      </header>

      <div id="govspeak">
        <p>
          When you get a pension you pay Income Tax on any money above your tax-free
          <a rel="external" href="http://www.gov.uk/income-tax-rates/personal-allowances">Personal Allowance</a>,
          just like you do on your salary.
        </p>

        <p>
          The only difference is that you can also <a href="/tax-on-your-pension/2">take part of your pension pot tax-free</a>.
          This is on top of your <span class="tooltip" title="The amount of income you can get tax free, before tax starts being applied to it">Personal Allowance</span>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <a href="/tax-on-your-pension/4">How much tax you pay</a> depends on your total income and the
          <a rel="external" href="http://www.gov.uk/income-tax-rates">tax rate</a> that applies to you.
        </p>

        <p>Your income may include:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>any money you get from your pension pot, eg as an <a href="/your-options/6">annuity</a> or <a href="/your-options/4">cash</a>
          </li>
          <li>the State Pension</li>
          <li>earnings from employment or self employment</li>
          <li>any other income, money from rental income</li>
          <li>any taxable benefits you might get, eg Carer’s Allowance</li>
        </ul>

        <p>If you leave your pension pot untouched and don’t take any money out, you don’t pay tax on it.</p>

        <div class="application-notice info-notice">
          <p>Use the <a href="/pension-tax-calculator">Pension tax calculator</a> to find out how much tax you pay if you cash in your whole pot.</p>
        </div>

